It all depends on the type of gunfight you're having. Try to find something similar to the fight you want to write. The fast-aced, stylized ones in The Raid are quite different from the more slow, desperate ones in something like Diehard or Spaghetti Westerns.
My advice would be to follow the same rules as a normal fight scene: Don't be a coreographer. It's going to be fast, so you shouldn't spend paragraphs describing exact movements or the scenery. Save that for moments of calm, if there are any.
Negligent Discharge has a few if you can stand femdom and greentext. Talia Day 7 (Resistance) has a good, drawn-out firefight that's really small scale, and Return has more over-the-top stuff since it's supernatural.

>Ambiance
Entirely dependant on the experience level of the character. If he's a rookie, then every shot that lands remotely close will have him ducking back and flinching. If he's a pro, only major things will be noticable, such as a comrade losing half a limb from not realizing they had their elbow out around a corner.
(Character) wants to move down a hallway under fire.
Inexperienced nigga:
>The ear shattering drumming from the enemy resonated through the halls as (character) clung tightly to the doorframe. Risking a peek, he was just barely able to see where the enemy was before a flurry of rounds impacted the wall next to him. He stumbled back, roaring in pain as debris from the shots shredded his face. Freshly bleeding from the head, and terrified beyond measure, he approached the doorframe again. The bastard had to run out of ammo soon, right?
This conveys directly that (character) is afraid. His injury from debris shows that he is vulnerable, and his lack of response to a difficult situation shows his lack of experience.
Experienced nigga:
>The ear shattering drumming from the enemy resonated through the halls as (character) clung tightly to the doorframe. He had watched (other character) lose his head from peeking, and he wasn't about to make the same mistakes. Priming a grenade, he roared a defiant cry, before sending the frag hurdling down the corridor. The shooting stopped for the briefest of moments replaced by shouting. The explosion shook the ground, and even being so far away, (character) felt the concussive force in his chest. He turned the corner and fired blindly at where the enemy should have been. If they had been alive after the grenade, they were sure as hell dead now.
Here, the loss of a minor character shows the price of a mistake. (Character) having a response without thinking about it shows training/experience. His aggression at the end shows more of the same.

>>57376778
If you really want to see what I mean, look at war footage from a certain ongoing eastern European conflict. Green troops will flinch away from fire constantly, and often fumble over themselves. Hardened troops barely notice that mortars are detonating next to them.
Tl;Dr is that if your boy is green, try to focus his perception on recoiling from things right next to him, and make it clear that he is overwhelmed. Fumbling with equipment, over obstacles, and receiving minor disorienting injuries is a plus.
If your boy is experienced, then he will be more aware of the bigger picture. He will react instantly to issues, and will be far more aggressive. Occasional flinching to nearby explosives, and minor character deaths to illustrate threats are a plus.
I know it's tempting, but do your best to avoid describing how "chaos and screams filled the air." That gets one line maximum, unless you're aiming for a bird's eye view.
